The algorithm¶

We will use the formulation described in the textbook (Learning from data, Abu-Mostafa et al.). Positive class label is equal to 1 and negative class label is equal to -1.

The loss (or cost) function to be minimized is $$ E_{in}(\mathbf{w}) = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N} \ln(1 + e^{-y^{(i)} \mathbf{w}^T \mathbf{x}^{(i)}}) \tag{1} $$

Its gradient is given by

$$\nabla E_{in}(\mathbf{w}) = - \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N} \frac{y^{(i)} \mathbf{x}^{(i)}}{1 + e^{y^{(i)} \mathbf{w}^T \mathbf{x}^{(i)}}} \tag{2}$$

The logistic (sigmoid) function is $$\sigma(z) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-z}} \tag{3}$$

1.1. Cross-entropy loss¶

This is Equation (1) above.

In [3]:
def cross_entropy_loss(w, X, y):
    """
    Computes the loss (equation 1)
    :param w: weight vector
    :type: np.ndarray(shape=(1+d, ))
    :param X: design matrix
    :type X: np.ndarray(shape=(N, 1+d))
    :param y: class labels
    :type y: np.ndarray(shape=(N, ))
    :return loss: loss (equation 1)
    :rtype: float
    """    
    
    ### ===> Your code begins here
    return np.sum(np.log(np.ones(X.shape[0]) + np.exp(-y*(np.dot(X, w)))))/X.shape[0]
    ### ===> Your code ends here

1.2. Gradient of the cross-entropy loss¶

This is Equation (2) above.

In [4]:
def cross_entropy_gradient(w, X, y):
    """
    Computes the gradient of the loss function (equation 2)
    :param w: weight vector
    :type: np.ndarray(shape=(1+d, ))
    :param X: design matrix
    :type X: np.ndarray(shape=(N, 1+d))
    :param y: class labels
    :type y: np.ndarray(shape=(N, ))
    :return grad: gradient (equation 2)
    :rtype: float
    """
    
    ### ===> Your code begins here 
    return -np.sum((X*y[:, np.newaxis])/(np.ones(X.shape[0]) + np.exp(y*(np.dot(X, w))))[:, np.newaxis], axis=0)/X.shape[0]
    ### ===> Your code ends here

1.3 Logistic regression training¶

The function below receives the data matrix X (shape = (N, d)) and the ouput vector y (shape = (N,)), and should return the final weight vector w (shape = (d+1,)) and, optionally (when parameter return_history = True), a list of size num_iterations+1 with the cross-entropy loss values at the beginning and after each of the iterations.

Note that the data matrix needs to be extended with a column of 1's.

If w0==None it must be initialized with w0 = np.random.normal(loc = 0, scale = 1, size = X.shape[1])

In [5]:
def train_logistic(X, y, learning_rate = 1e-1, w0 = None,\
                        num_iterations = 1000, return_history = False):
    """
    Computes the weight vector applying the gradient descent technique
    :param X: design matrix
    :type X: np.ndarray(shape=(N, d))
    :param y: class label
    :type y: np.ndarray(shape=(N, ))
    :return: weight vector
    :rtype: np.ndarray(shape=(1+d, ))
    :return: the history of loss values (optional)
    :rtype: list of float
    """    
     
    ### ===> Your code begins here
    X = np.hstack((np.ones((X.shape[0], 1)), X))
    
    if w0 is None:
        w0 = np.random.normal(loc = 0, scale = 1, size = X.shape[1])
        
    loss_hist = [(cross_entropy_loss(w0, X, y), cross_entropy_loss(w0, X, y))]
    
    #SGD
    for it in range(num_iterations):
        w0 = w0 - learning_rate*cross_entropy_gradient(w0, X, y)
        if return_history:
            loss_hist.append((loss_hist[-1][1], cross_entropy_loss(w0, X, y)))
    
    
    #SGD + Momentum
    '''
    step = 0
    beta = 0.99
    for it in range(num_iterations):
        step = beta*step + (1-beta)*cross_entropy_gradient(w0, X, y)
        w0 = w0 - learning_rate*step
        if return_history:
            loss_hist.append((loss_hist[-1][1], cross_entropy_loss(w0, X, y)))
    '''
    
    return w0, loss_hist
    ### ===> Your code ends here

1.4. Logistic regression prediction¶

The function in the next cell will be used to do the prediction of logistic regression. Recall that the prediction is a score in $[0,1]$, given by the sigmoid value of the linear combination.

In [6]:
def sigmoid(z):
    return 1 / (1 + np.exp(-z))


def predict_logistic(X, w):
    """
    Computes the logistic regression prediction
    :param X: design matrix
    :type X: np.ndarray(shape=(N,d))
    :param w: weight vector
    :rtype: np.ndarray(shape=(1+d,))
    :return: predicted classes 
    :rtype: np.ndarray(shape=(N,))
    """
    
    ### ===> Your code begins here
    X = np.hstack((np.ones((X.shape[0], 1)), X))
    return sigmoid(np.dot(X, w))
    ### ===> Your code ends here

3.4 How good is the separation?¶

Based on the predicted probabilities, we can decide the final class label for each example $\mathbf{x}$ as follows:

$$\mbox{class label of $\mathbf{x}$} = \left\{ \begin{array}{ll} +1, & \mbox{if $\hat{P}(y=1|\mathbf{x}) > 0.5$,}\\ -1, & \mbox{if $\hat{P}(y=1|\mathbf{x}) \leq 0.5$}\\ \end{array} \right.$$

4. MNIST Dataset¶

This is a well known dataset, commonly used as a first example to illustrate image classification tasks. We could say it is the "Hello world!" of image classification. It consists of handwritten digits, divided into $60000$ training images and $10000$ test images. All images are gray-scale (one channel with pixel intensities varying from 0 to 255) and have size $28 \times 28$. There are 10 classes, corresponding to digits 0 to 9.

We could use the $28 \times 28$ pixel intensities as features. However, here we will perform feature extraction from the images and then the classification based on the extracted features.

The dataset is available in many places. Here we will use the one available with Keras [1]. More information on MNIST can be found at the oficial site.

[1]: Franois Chollet and others, Keras, https://keras.io, 2015

===> Your comments here

We can observe that distribution of digits is very similiar which is awesome. We typically prefer to classify examples from the same distribution we have learned from. If we try to classify a test set that comes from another distribution, it could affect a lot our performance metrics. Although it is very nice to have that kind of comparison, looking at our test set could be considered data snooping. Hence, in a perfect scenario, we would pick all of our data from one distribution and then randomly separate it in training and testing sets.

4.2. Feature extraction¶

Note that the images consist of 2828=784 pixel values and they could be used as "raw features" of the images. However, here we will extract some features from the images and perform classification using them instead of the pixel values.

Mean intensity¶

In the book Learning from Data [2], one of the attributes (features) used by the authors is the mean intensity of the pixel values. This feature is directly related to the proportion of the pixels corresponding to the digit in the image. For instance, it is reasonable to expect that a digit 5 or 2 occupies more pixels than the digit 1 and, therefore, the mean intensity of the first two should be larger than that of the digit 1.

Symmetry¶

The second attribute used by the authors is horizontal symmetry.

Symmetry will be defined in terms of asymetry. We define asymmetry as the pixelwise mean of the absolute difference between the pixels values from the original image and those from the corresponding horizotally flipped image. Then, symmetry is defined as the negative of asymmetry.

[2]: Yaser S Abu-Mostafa, Malik Magdon-Ismail, and Hsuan-Tien Lin, Learning from Data, 2012

In [31]:
def mean_intensity(image):
    return np.mean(image)

def Hsimmetry(image):
    # The processing below invert the order of the columns of the image
    reflected_image = image[:, ::-1]
    return -np.mean(np.abs(image - reflected_image))

Normalization of feature values is a common procedure. Here we apply the z-score formula. Note that the normalization parameters (mean and standard deviation) are computed only on training data. To normalize the test data, we use the same parameters. (We suggest you to think why we should not compute the mean and standard deviation over the training+test set. There is no need to answer this here.)

In [34]:
# Adjust the scale of feature values; standardize them.
# (Yes, the features in the test set should be standardized using
#  the statistics of the features in the training set) -- why ??
for i in range(X_train_features.shape[1]):
    avg = np.mean(X_train_features[:, i])
    stddev = np.std(X_train_features[:, i])
    X_train_features[:, i] = (X_train_features[:, i] - avg) / stddev
    X_test_features[:, i] = (X_test_features[:, i] - avg) / stddev

print("Shape of X_train: ", X_train_features.shape)

def shuffle(X, y):
    # input and output must be shuffled equally
    perm = np.random.permutation(len(X))
    return X[perm], y[perm]

Confusion matrix (training set)¶

Recall that the logistic regression returns a score $\hat{p}$ in $[0,1]$, which can be interpreted as the probability $p(y=1|\mathbf{x})$. To compute the confusion matrix, one needs to choose a threshold value $T$ to decide the final class label (that is $\hat{y} = 1 \Longleftrightarrow \hat{p} \geq T$ ).

Play with the threshold value in the code (following cell). Did you manage to find a threshold value (other than 0.5) that improves accuracy? How threshold relates to TP, FP, TN and FN ? Comment.

===> Your comment here

To experiment a little bit with the various threshold values, I tried using numpy linspace function. Considering all the tested values, in terms of accuracy, the best value seems to be only a little off the conventional (0.55). Now talking about the other metrics, we had pretty much the expected outcomes. When we have a small threshold, we got almost every TP, almost no FN, a big mount of FP and a significant but not huge amount of TN. As we increase a little the threshold, things start to normalize a little bit, so the numbers of FN and TN grew and the numbers of TP and FP got smaller. When we start to make the threshold really big, though, we go back to a strange case where the numbers of FN and TN are big - specially the enormous TN -, but the numbers of TP and FP are much smaller - specially the tiny FP.

In [40]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(y, y_pred):
    """
    It receives an array with the ground-truth (y)
    and another with the prediction (y_pred), both with binary labels
    (positve=+1 and negative=-1) and plots the confusion
    matrix.
    It uses P (positive class id) and N (negative class id)
    which are "global" variables ...
    """
    TP = np.sum((y_pred == 1) * (y == 1))
    TN = np.sum((y_pred == -1) * (y == -1))

    FP = np.sum((y_pred == 1) * (y == -1))
    FN = np.sum((y_pred == -1) * (y == 1))

    total = TP+FP+TN+FN
    print("TP = %4d    FP = %4d\nFN = %4d    TN = %4d"%(TP,FP,FN,TN))
    print("Accuracy = %d / %d (%f)\n" %((TP+TN),total, (TP+TN)/total))
    confusion = [
        [TP/(TP+FN), FP/(TN+FP)],
        [FN/(TP+FN), TN/(TN+FP)]
    ]

    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(confusion, \
                         ['$\hat{y} = %d$'%P, '$\hat{y} = %d$'%N],\
                         ['$y = %d$'%P, '$y = %d$'%N])
    plt.figure(figsize = (8,4))
    sb.set(font_scale=1.4)
    sb.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True) #, annot_kws={"size": 16}, cmap = 'coolwarm')
    plt.show()
    
    
threshold = np.linspace(0.1, 0.9, 17)

p_hat = predict_logistic(X_train, w_logistic)
for thresh in threshold:
    print("Threshold: {}".format(thresh))
    y_hat = np.where(p_hat > thresh, 1, -1)

    total = len(y_hat)

    plot_confusion_matrix(y_train, y_hat)

===> Your comments here

For the first experiment I tried was to increase the number of training examples to 1000, but still maintaining a balanced set. By doing this, I increased our accuracy on the training set by a little bit, I changed the best threshold to 0.45, and I also increased a little bit the accuracy on the test set.

Now for the second experiment I tried to use an unbalanced set with 100 positive examples and 500 negative examples. This experiment changed a lot the separation surface and also increased the training accuracy by a significant amount - 0.91% now. The accuracy of the test also changed a lot. I lost a little more than 10% of accuracy.

The third experiment was very similar to the second one, but trying to unbalance the training set the other way. The results of this experiment were a little more interesting. I again got a completely different separation surface, but now I lost a bit of training accuracy and changed the best threshold to 0.35. I also increased a lot the test accuracy - about 10% better than the orignial assingment.

The forth experiment was completely different from the former ones. In this experiment, I tried to change the pair of classes analysed and increasing a bit the number of training examples, but still maintaining a balanced set. For the experiments changing the 5 class to other digits - 2, 3 and 8 -, I got only a better results in terms of accuracy in test sets - from 2% to 9% better. When changing the 1 class to other digits - 3 and 8 -, I lost a lot of test accuracy - from 23% to 30% worst. this phenomenon probably happened because the digits other than 1 are much more similar to each other according to the features we are using.

Finally using the scikit-lear library to implement the logistic regression on our data - 200 balanced examples for the 5 and 1 classes -, I got a different separation surface, which was a little worse in terms of training accuracy than ours - about 2% -, but much better in terms of testing accuracy than ours - about 11%.
